	<article class="post-1325 post type-post status-publish hentry tag-after-deadline tag-grammar" id="post-1325">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
					</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Beware the Missing Link</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Philip B. Corbett			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-12-16T13:00:07+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">December 16, 2014 8:00 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">December 16, 2014 8:00 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//afterdeadline.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/12/16/beware-the-missing-link/" data-title="Beware the Missing Link" data-description="For all our progress in digital journalism, we still sometimes neglect one of its most basic tools: the link.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For all our progress in digital journalism, we sometimes still neglect one of its most basic tools: the link.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Online readers today simply expect links and find their absence baffling or worse. Links provide background information, buttress our reporting, point to related material, aid search and help ensure proper credit and attribution. They are easy to include and cost nothing.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">They should be as routine in our stories as quotes, and for many reporters they are. But we still miss many opportunities.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Times&#8217;s stylebook offers writers and editors this guidance:</p>
<blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If an article refers to material of interest to readers, such as a website, document, image or video, provide an embedded link as a convenience. Readers also value links to background information and other useful content. When crediting a competitor, providing a link is mandatory. Test that all links are operational. While readers understand that The Times does not edit or control material found through external links, be mindful of our taste standards and generally avoid linking to strongly offensive material. Consult the standards editor or the news desk if there are questions. Generally avoid linking directly to the site of a specific seller for products including books, unless the website itself is the topic. &hellip;</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So, how well are we linking? We could do a lot better. My colleague Patrick LaForge offered these recent examples where we fell short.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Traveling through the &#8220;economically struggling&#8221; nation, Mr. Dalrymple told the crowd, he encountered many people who asked, &#8220;Jack, what the heck are you doing out there in North Dakota?&#8221; to create the fastest-growing economy, lowest unemployment rate and (<strong>according to one survey</strong>) happiest population.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We should have pointed to the <a href="//www.gallup.com/poll/167435/north-dakota-well-being-west-virginia-still-last.aspx">Gallup poll itself</a>, as one reader <a href="//stevebuttry.wordpress.com/2014/11/24/linking-at-the-new-york-times-encouraged-but-inconsistent/">pointed out.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Speaking Monday at a news conference in Clayton, Mo., Robert P. McCulloch, the St. Louis County prosecutor, described the <strong>series of events</strong> that led to the shooting, as well as the evidence presented to the 12-member grand jury. He detailed an altercation inside Officer Wilson&#8217;s vehicle, after which Officer Wilson had Mr. Brown&#8217;s blood on his weapon, shirt and pants, the prosecutor said, as well as swelling and redness on his face.</em> &hellip;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Mr. Brown&#8217;s mother, Lesley McSpadden, and stepfather, Louis Head, <strong>stood with protesters</strong> outside the barricaded Ferguson police station as Mr. McCulloch made the decision public. As Ms. McSpadden cried, Mr. Head turned and yelled, with an expletive injected, &#8220;Burn this down!&#8221;</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the first passage, we should have linked to our <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/11/26/us/ferguson-grand-jury-weighed-mass-of-evidence-much-of-it-conflicting.html">testimony</a> reporting and the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/11/25/us/evidence-released-in-michael-brown-case.html">document viewer</a>. Besides alerting readers to valuable background material, this might have helped with search optimization. In the second, we should have linked to the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/us/100000003255335/ferguson-weeps-then-burns.html?playlistId=1194811622182">video</a> of the family reacting to the news, which many readers would obviously want to see.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>&#8220;Gov. Andrew M. Cuomo didn&#8217;t just order boots on the ground from Albany; he has put his own boots on our snow-clogged streets,&#8221; The Buffalo News <strong>said in an editorial</strong>  on Tuesday, which also praised Mayor Byron W. Brown and the Erie County executive, Mark C. Poloncarz.</em> &hellip;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>&#8220;You are incredibly wrong,&#8221; Ari Sarsalari, a Weather Channel meteorologist, <strong>posted on Twitter</strong>. The weatherman Al Roker also <strong>took to Twitter</strong> to defend the Weather Service, and to scold the governor.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The links to <a href="//www.buffalonews.com/opinion/buffalo-news-editorials/officials-demonstrated-real-leadership-in-coping-with-our-snow-disaster-20141125">the editorial</a> and <a href="https://www.twitter.com/AriWeather/status/536537007926030337">the tweets</a> were <a href="https://www.twitter.com/alroker/status/536600941848719363">added later</a>. They should have been in there when the article was first published.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>The Federal Aviation Administration has said that drones raise safety concerns, like running into people and planes. On Wednesday, the agency said it receives about <strong>25 reports a month</strong> of drones operating near manned aircraft. The agency is expected to propose new rules for commercial use as early as next month.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This article was full of great links, but it was missing one: <a href="//bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/11/26/new-f-a-a-report-tallies-drone-sightings-highlighting-safety-issues/">a link to a Bits post about the F.A.A.&#8217;s decision</a>. Readers on phones need a little more help. Don&#8217;t force them to search.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Set for release in the United States on Dec. 19, and around the world on dates that stretch into March, &#8220;<strong>Night at the Museum: Secret of the Tomb</strong>&#8221; is the third and last entry in a comedy series that has surprised even its makers with its durability and international appeal. <strong>The original film</strong>, which was directed by Mr. Levy and also starred Mr. Stiller, opened in 2006 to $30.4 million in first-weekend ticket sales.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This article had no links. At a minimum, we should have linked to <a href="//www.nightatthemuseummovie.com/?gclid=CLmKgPappcICFcpAMgodlEkAsQ">a trailer</a> for the new film and our review of <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2006/12/22/movies/22muse.html">the original</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>On Nov. 24, shortly before 8:30 p.m., as hundreds of protesters who were assembled outside the police station here learned Officer Wilson was not being charged, Mr. Head embraced Mr. Brown&#8217;s mother, Lesley McSpadden, on the hood of a car. Protesters had been listening to the announcement on loudspeakers and car stereos, and the family&#8217;s <strong>reaction was videotaped</strong> and published by The New York Times.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We should have linked to <a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/us/100000003254183/michael-browns-mother-reacts.html">our own video</a>. (We did, eventually.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>A Staten Island grand jury declined to indict Officer Daniel Pantaleo in the choking death of Eric Garner. The New York City medical examiner had ruled that Mr. Garner&#8217;s death was a homicide, caused by a chokehold and compression of his chest during an attempted arrest. While the jurors&#8217; rationale was not made public, here are some of the legal issues that they may have considered, as well as some of Officer Pantaleo&#8217;s testimony. The images below are from a video obtained by The New York Daily News.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While this chart did have a link elsewhere to the day&#8217;s news article and the video itself, each of these sentences in the introductory paragraph was a lost opportunity to link into past articles in our archive.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>The battle over the report&#8217;s conclusions has been waged behind closed doors for years, and provided the backdrop to the more recent fight over <strong>the C.I.A.&#8217;s penetration of a computer network</strong> used by committee staff members working on the investigation.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We should have provided the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/08/01/world/senate-intelligence-commitee-cia-interrogation-report.html">background for readers</a> who may have missed that earlier revelation.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&nbsp;<br />
<strong>In a Word</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This week&#8217;s grab bag of grammar, style and other missteps, compiled with help from colleagues and readers.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>These investors helped the platform issue $177 million in loans last month alone, <strong>three and a half times more</strong> than in October 2013.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Avoid this ambiguous &#8220;times more&#8221; expression. The stylebook says this:</p>
<blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>times less, times more</strong>. Writers who speak of <em>three times more</em> or <em>three times faster</em> often mean &#8220;multiplied by 3,&#8221; but precise readers are likely to understand the meaning as &#8220;multiplied by 4&#8243;: the original quantity or speed, plus three <em>more times</em>. For clarity, avoid <em>times more</em>, <em>times faster</em>, <em>times bigger</em>, etc. Write <em>four times as much</em> (or <em>as fast</em>, etc.). And do not write <em>times less</em> or <em>times smaller</em> (or things like <em>times as thin</em> or <em>times as short</em>). A quantity can <em>decrease</em> only one time before disappearing, and then there is nothing left to decrease further. Make it <em>one-third as much</em> (or <em>as tall</em>, or <em>as fast</em>).</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Ticket revenue in North America has fallen <strong>4 percent this year compared to the same period</strong> in 2013, according to box office analysts, and attendance is equally down.</em> &hellip;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>The decline has hammered the biggest theater companies, with profit at both AMC and Regal Entertainment, the No. 1 chain, plunging <strong>more than 50 percent through the first nine months of this year, compared to the same period</strong> a year earlier.</em> &hellip;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Last year, despite a glut of extravagant action movies, the number of frequent moviegoers ages 18 to 24 <strong>dropped 17 percent, compared to a year earlier</strong>; the 12-to-17 age bracket dropped 13 percent.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In each case, make it &#8220;compared with.&#8221; The stylebook says this:</p>
<blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>compare</strong>. Use <em>compare to</em> when the intent is to liken things: <em>The book compared the quarterback&#8217;s role to the job of a company&#8217;s vice president for operations</em>. When the intent is to compare and contrast, or just to contrast, use <em>compare with</em>: <em>They compared Terry&#8217;s forecasting with Dana&#8217;s, and found Dana more accurate</em>.</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>In recent years, at least one member of the royal family has suggested that <strong>admiration for the monarchy have fallen</strong> among young people.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Make it &#8220;admiration &hellip; has fallen,&#8221; of course.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Now <strong>anyone</strong> can get past the park&#8217;s <strong>wrought iron</strong> gates, and <strong>they</strong> do not even have to leave home.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The plural &#8220;they&#8221; does not agree with the singular &#8220;anyone.&#8221; The problem could easily be avoided: &#8220;Now anyone can get past the park&#8217;s wrought-iron gates, without even having to leave home.&#8221; (Also note that as a modifier, &#8220;wrought-iron&#8221; should have a hyphen.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>But <strong>the other reason</strong> that the civil-rights era comparisons were inapt <strong>is because</strong> the nature of racism has changed.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Make it &#8220;the other reason &hellip; is that the nature of racism has changed.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><strong>The decline</strong> in the city&#8217;s crime rate, <strong>while deeper in many categories than other cities</strong>, mirrors a nationwide downward trend from heights of violent crime in the 1990s.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As written, this compares the New York decline to other cities, rather than to the decline in other cities. One simple fix: Use the plural possessive, &#8220;than other cities&#8217;.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><strong>TITANS&#8217;S</strong> HUNTER ON I.R. Tennessee placed wide receiver Justin Hunter on injured reserve while he is still in a Houston hospital recovering from a lacerated spleen.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There&#8217;s an extraneous &#8220;s&#8221; here.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Mr. Calatrava and his partners said that the impact and utility of the Oculus would be diminished if it were <strong>shrunken</strong> further, that the temporary station did not meet requirements for circulation of air and pedestrians, and that columns would interrupt visitors&#8217; movement and provide a potential target for bombers.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Our newsroom dictionary (Webster&#8217;s New World College) prefers &#8220;shrunk&#8221; for the past participle.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>All of those people declined <strong>to speak with either lawyers conducting the inquiry for the governor or with the legislative committee,</strong> which has eight Democrats and four Republicans.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Not parallel. After &#8220;or&#8221; we have the complete prepositional phrase, but after &#8220;either&#8221; we don&#8217;t. Remove the second &#8220;with,&#8221; or put &#8220;either&#8221; before the first &#8220;with.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><strong>Thirty-three years ago,</strong> August Montalbano said, he took his final gulp of alcohol and <strong>has been a regular attendee</strong> of Alcoholics Anonymous meetings ever since.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This construction suggests that the time element applies to the entire clause, including &#8220;has been a regular attendee,&#8221; which is not right. Make that a separate clause by giving the verb its own subject: &#8220;&hellip; and he has been a regular attendee &hellip;&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>City officials affirmed on Thursday that <strong>an internal police investigation, as well as a federal inquiry, were active</strong>.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Make it &#8220;was active.&#8221; The prepositional phrase beginning &#8220;as well as&#8221; is parenthetical and does not make the subject plural.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><strong>That nuance, and the mayor&#8217;s reluctance</strong> to engage with questions he dislikes, <strong>was</strong> put to a sharp, nationally televised test on Sunday morning, when Mr. de Blasio faced tough questions during an appearance on ABC&#8217;s &#8220;This Week.&#8221;</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Here we have the opposite problem. Commas or no commas, &#8220;nuance&#8221; and &#8220;reluctance&#8221; are joined by the coordinating conjunction &#8220;and,&#8221; so they make a compound subject and should get a plural verb.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Still, in Ferguson, some whites said they felt <strong>like</strong> blacks had rushed to judgment in condemning them as bigots.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Make it &#8220;as if,&#8221; &#8220;as though&#8221; or &#8220;that&#8221; &mdash; not &#8220;like.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><strong>Like an animal</strong> whose biorhythms propel it into survivalist and cyclical activity, <strong>the chilling of the air</strong> and <strong>the shedding of the deciduous trees each year</strong> lull me, in a way that feels both joyous and uncontrollable, into a state of covetousness that only the Vermont Country Store can quell.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A dangler. The chilling and shedding are not &#8220;like an animal.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Metro, 12/8:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>On Monday night, the couple will attend a Brooklyn Nets game at the Barclays Center, where a possible <strong>confab</strong> with two arena regulars, BeyoncÃ© and Jay Z, has been rumored.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Hard to see any reason for the dated colloquialism &#8220;confab.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><strong>Inflation is due to rise 9 percent this year</strong> and to continue climbing.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Inflation will not rise 9 percent; the cost of living is expected to rise 9 percent, so that is the (projected) inflation rate. Rephrase.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>[Picture caption] Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu with Tzipi Livni, his justice minister <strong>who</strong> he fired last week, along with another centrist member of his coalition government.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Make it &#8220;whom,&#8221; the direct object of &#8220;fired.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Average people find it difficult to place themselves in the shoes of police officers who live <strong>everyday</strong> knowing their next call could be their last.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As one word, this is an adjective meaning usual or ordinary. We wanted two words, &#8220;every day.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Gasol&#8217;s mother still lives in the Memphis area (his father returned to Spain with their youngest son, Adria) to be near Marc&#8217;s wife and their young child, and the Gasols still have the same seats, and family passes with the same photos, that they had when FedEx Forum opened 10 years ago.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This overstuffed sentence is very difficult to decipher.</p>
	</div>
